3.0 of 5 bubbles
Exorbitant cost, waaay overrated experience
Apr 2014 ‚Ä¢ Couples
We loved Vietnam and I used TA reviews religiously to plan our trip, but in this case I let those reviews overrule my gut feeling ‚Äî that a Halong Bay cruise would be a costly mistake. What drove me was my worry that we'd regret not going and never know if we'd made a mistake. So that was the first error in judgment. The second was booking a "luxury" cruise knowing that it isn't our traveling style. But I wasn't aware of any other options. If it were possible, I would have liked to take a 2-hour ride on a small boat with a guide and call it a day. (Also, the 4-hour journey from Hanoi is long and the scenery unremarkable.)
We chose the highly rated Indochina Sails because we wanted the experience to be as positive as possible. But it just felt so fakey and not Vietnamese, aimed at pleasing Western tastes and palates. The boat was way too big for the number of people on it. The food was fine, but a few months later I don't remember it at all.
There were a few tours off the boat, one to see the floating village (the residents obviously were used to tourists coming by, and I'm guessing/hoping they are compensated in some way, but it was as if they were on display). We also walked through a cave and climbed to a lookout (400-something stairs) with tons of other tourists. Both sites were interesting, but I was so hot I thought I'd fall over. And this was in April, not even summer! But that's just me, maybe.
So in the end, I very much regret having spent a large sum of money, over $430 (plus drinks on the boat) for the experience. We don't spend that way, ever. It was especially incongruous since Vietnam is so affordable and we stayed in beautiful hotels for under $50/night! I guess the pricing is what the market will bear. My advice to anyone who thinks like me: follow your instincts. The photos of Halong Bay are lovely, and that should be enough.
Written December 30, 2014
chris_phillips_79
Brisbane, Australia13 contributions
1.0 of 5 bubbles
Over promised and under delivered
Oct 2014 ‚Ä¢ Couples
One of the biggest problems with booking tours in Vietnam is the tour agencies. None of them have the same prices so it's hard to know what you are getting, and they always tell you it includes everything you ask for, but it doesn't.
If you book Halong Bay do yourself a favour and book the 4 star as I haven't heard anyone complain about it yet. Almost everyone we met had a rubbish experience on the 2 star.
If your budget is like ours and you have to take the cheaper option you absolutely must shop around. We paid US$95 for the 3 day trip and another guy paid $85 and some paid $135. The guy who paid $85 had the bungalow on the island included as well, you want the bungalow as the hotel sucks. Probably the most important thing you need to do when booking is get the tour operator to write everything that you want included on the ticket. This can include free alcohol, free water, kayaking, rock climbing, trip to monkey island and yes the night in the bungalow (make sure they write the word bungalow or you will end up in the hotel). I would also suggest you take a photo of the brochure so you can read back over what should be included and also show the guides, and take a photo of your ticket, in case it goes missing.
My last bit of advice is avoid the boat Dragon Pearl, it has a lean to one side and smells like poo, the staff are really unfriendly and don't really want you there. Also take water with you, it's expensive on the boats.
Halong Bay is the worst tour I have ever been on, but it doesn't have to be if you know what to expect.
Written November 21, 2014
Star1126
